@Reasoning:
Banner emitted once at startup. Separator width (36 "=") matches the
title length so the heading boxes cleanly in CI logs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate title and "=" rule via StringCore, print each, deallocate.
Always returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_header" returns Integer:
    Let header be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "HTML to HIR Translation Test Suite"
    proc print with header
    proc deallocate from Layout with header

    Let separator be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "===================================="
    proc print with separator
    proc deallocate from Layout with separator

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"[PASS] <name>" line shared by all 10 test_* procs in this file.
Centralized so formatting is identical across the suite.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate "[PASS] " prefix, print prefix and caller-owned test_name,
deallocate the prefix.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_test_success" takes test_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let pass_msg be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "[PASS] "
    proc print with pass_msg
    proc print with test_name
    proc deallocate from Layout with pass_msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"[FAIL] <name>" line. Single-arg signature because each test_* proc
passes a pre-formatted "<scenario>: failed" string, baking the reason
into the name.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate "[FAIL] " prefix, print prefix and caller-owned test_name,
deallocate the prefix.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_test_failure" takes test_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let fail_msg be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "[FAIL] "
    proc print with fail_msg
    proc print with test_name
    proc deallocate from Layout with fail_msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Final summary block matching peer HTML suites. Reads counters through
type-checked struct field access (results.total etc.) at the report
site, complementing the raw memory_get_int64 path used inside each
test_* proc.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print "=" separator, "Test Results:" heading, then Total/Passed/Failed
lines. Each label allocated/printed/deallocated; numbers via print_int.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_results" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let separator be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "===================================="
    proc print with separator
    proc deallocate from Layout with separator

    Let summary be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "Test Results:"
    proc print with summary
    proc deallocate from Layout with summary

    Let total_msg be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "Total: "
    proc print with total_msg
    proc print_int with results.total
    proc deallocate from Layout with total_msg

    Let passed_msg be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "Passed: "
    proc print with passed_msg
    proc print_int with results.passed
    proc deallocate from Layout with passed_msg

    Let failed_msg be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "Failed: "
    proc print with failed_msg
    proc print_int with results.failed
    proc deallocate from Layout with failed_msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Local integer formatter so this suite has no dependency on stdlib
formatting allocators. Zero and negative inputs are handled explicitly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. value == 0 -> print "0", return.
2. Allocate 32-byte buffer; walk position from 31 downward writing
   48 + (temp % 10), dividing temp by 10 each pass.
3. For negatives, operate on -temp and write '-' (45) at the final
   position.
4. Increment position, print buffer+position as a C string, deallocate.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_int" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is equal to 0:
        Let zero be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "0"
        proc print with zero
        proc deallocate from Layout with zero
        Return 1
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    Let position be 31
    Let temp be value

    If temp is less than 0:
        Set temp to -temp
    End If

    While temp is greater than 0:
        Let digit be temp modulo by 10
        Let char be 48 plus digit
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, position, char
        Set position to position minus 1
        Set temp to temp divided by 10
    End While

    If value is less than 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, position, 45
        Set position to position minus 1
    End If

    Set position to position plus 1
    Let str_ptr be buffer plus position
    proc print with str_ptr

    proc deallocate from Layout with buffer

    Return 1
End Process

Note: End of HTML to HIR Translation Test Suite
